Part I - (Fordgobike data Exploration)¶

by (Cynthia Undisa)¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual bike rides of 183412 columns and 16 rows made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. In depth data exploration using univariate exploration, bivariate exploration and multivariate exploration and explanation is done on the Fordgobike data.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Univariate Exploration¶

In [8]:
binsize = 500
bins = np.arange(0, bike['duration_sec'].max()+binsize, binsize)
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = bike, x='duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
plt.axis([-500, 10000,0, 90000])
plt.title('Trip vs Duration')
plt.show()

Observation

It has a long tail so we transform it using log

In [9]:
#axis transformation to log
bin = 0.05
log_bins = 10**np.arange(2.4,np.log(bike['duration_sec'].max())+ bin, bin)
plt.figure(figsize=[9, 5])
plt.hist(data = bike, x='duration_sec', bins= log_bins)
plt.xlabel('Duration(sec)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4], [500, '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k'])
plt.axis([0, 10000, 0, 15000])
plt.title('trip vs Durations')
plt.show()

#plotting age vs number of users using histogram
binsize = 1
bins = np.arange(0, bike['Age'].astype(float).max()+binsize, binsize)
plt.figure(figsize=[9,5])
plt.hist(data = bike, x='Age',bins=bins)
plt.xlim(20,80)
plt.xlabel('Age(years)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Users')
plt.title('Age vs number of users')
plt.show()

Observation

bike trip users are concentrated between 25 to 45 years old.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration has a very long tail so I transformed it using log and found that the peak occurs at 600 seconds starting from 0

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Start time and end time are converted to datetime, Birth year is converted by subtracting current year from birth year this action is performed as age gives a better percerption.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Exploring the relationship between two categorical measures gender, user type and trip duration and age I wish to know if trip duration is dependent on gender, user_type and age.

In [22]:
#referred to stackoverflow
gender_markers = [['Male', 'o'], ['Female', 's'], ['Other', 'v']]
for gender, marker in gender_markers:
    df_gender = bike[bike['member_gender'] == gender]
    plt.scatter(df_gender['Age'], df_gender['duration_sec'], marker = marker,s=10,alpha=0.25)
plt.legend(['Male', 'Female', 'Other'])
plt.axis([10,120, 0,10000])
plt.xlabel('Age(year)')
plt.ylabel('Duration(sec)')
plt.title('Age vs duration')
plt.show()

Observation

I will use facet grid so that the different variables can be clearly seen

In [23]:
#referred to stackoverflow
#Using facet grid
genders = sb.FacetGrid(data = bike, col = 'member_gender',height =6)
genders.map(plt.scatter, 'Age', 'duration_sec',s=10,alpha=0.25)
genders.set_xlabels('Age (year)')
genders.set_ylabels('duration_sec')
plt.xlim(10,120) 
plt.ylim(0,10000)
plt.show()

Observation

the duration_sec is higher for males than for females and other.

user_types = sb.FacetGrid(data = bike, col = 'user_type',height =6)

plt.show()

Observation

Subscriber user type take longer duration trip than customer. Mostly subscribers below 80 take part in bike trips, mostly customers below 70 are the one who take part in bike trips

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

duration_sec is higher for males than for females and other. Subscriber user type take longer duration trip than customers. Mostly subscribers below 80 take part in bike trips, mostly customers below 70 are the one who take part in bike trips

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The age bracket of subscribers (20-80) who take part in bike trips is longer than the customers (20-70)

Conclusions¶

Though males have a higher trip duration the total percent is higher for females than for males.Subscriber user type have a longer duration than customer user type. Bike trip users are concentrated between ages 25-45 years old.Number of male users are more than those of female and other gender. *Only a small number of subscribers are the ones who bike share less than 2000.
